<P>
Two newspapers that identified a source who had been promised anonymity must 
pay him $200,000 in compensatory damages but not the $500,000 in punitive 
damages also awarded by a Hennepin County jury, the Minnesota Court of Appeals 
said. The First Amendment guarantee of press freedom does not protect the Star 
Tribune of Minneapolis or the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch from liability 
under contract laws, in this case their reporters' oral promises of 
confidentiality, the three-judge panel said in upholding the compensatory 
damage award. But the court rejected public relations man Dan Cohen's claim of 
misrepresentation and said he is not entitled to punitive damages. 
