<DATELINE>
<P>
PALMER, Alaska 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A strong earthquake in a remote area of the Alaskan peninsula Monday morning 
caused minor damage in the town of Chignik and sloshed oil stored at a refinery 
400 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
The quake, measured at magnitude 6.9, was centered 70 miles southeast of 
Chignik. The Alaska Tsunami Warning Center issued a tidal wave warning for 
coastal Alaska and British Columbia, but the resulting wave was less than 6 
inches high at Sand Point, Alaska. Workers at the Tesoro Refinery in Kenai, 400 
miles away, felt the quake and reported sloshing in oil storage tanks. 
