<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Pittsburgh Steelers, who open their season at home against the Cleveland 
Browns Sunday, haven't even been able to get around the Rolling Stones. 
</P>
<P>
The Stones' first Pittsburgh concert in 17 years Wednesday night means the 
Steelers won't be able to practice in Three Rivers Stadium until Friday. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a distraction and a hardship from our normal practice routine," said Joe 
Gordon, the team's business manager. "This is the first time since Three Rivers 
opened (in 1970) that I can remember this happening the week of the home 
opener." 
</P>
<P>
Until then, the Steelers will practice on their nearby grass practice field, 
which they normally use only when they play teams with natural turf fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
