<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
TRAINER FINDS VICTORY HAIR-RAZING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yankees trainer Gene Monahan, completing a promise he made just after the 
All-Star break, shaved his head Monday after the team's season-high fifth 
straight victory. 
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes you have to sacrifice vanity for intensity," he said. 
</P>
<P>
After the Yankees beat the California Angels 2-1, Monahan sat in the trainer's 
room while five players attacked his mop of thick black hair. Jesse Barfield 
started with a pair of scissors, doing "most of the damage," he said. Mel Hall 
finished with a razor. 
</P>
<P>
"He cooperated fully," Barfield said. "He really showed me something." 
</P>
<P>
Monahan, a Yankees trainer for 17 years, made his promise during the New 
York-Kansas City series in mid-July. At the time, the Yankees had won as many 
as four straight only once -- in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Gene Monahan 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
